<br>
As for spells casted by pets onto a mob.  For a spell to land on a mob, the mob must be within 1/3 of the caster's level above him/her.  At level 60, this means you can hit any mob that is level 80 or below.  At 49, this means the max is 65.  Most red trash mobs go up to 65, and boss mobs are 70+.  Pets can cast on the trash, but not bosses.  Of course, the rules for casting on a player are different.<br>
<br>
Lure spells I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> think</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> follow the same rule set, but have a modifier.  There are actually 4 types of Lures.  Lure(3) - moderate resist, Lure(4) - hard to resist, Lure(5) - very hard to resist, Lure(6) - extremely hard to resist.  Lure spells are noted by having a negative cha attribute, and the number of charisma (3,4,5,6) is what tells you the level of Lure.  An example is the shroom curse in FG is level 3, several NWing AE's (such as Mira's silence) are level 4, wizard nukes are level 5, and Feeblemind (THO) is level 6.  It is my understanding that they follow the same rule set, and perhaps the level is a magnifier (such as Feeblemid is 6x as likely to land as a normal spell).  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> If</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> thats correct, then pets still won't land on most boss mobs.<br>
<br>
There's a second set of rules, marked as &quot;Dragon Resistance&quot;, which are basicly lure spells.  However, they follow a different set of rules, and a different formula for landing.  I honestly don't know how this rule set works, other than its hard to resist.  Its possible that pets could land a dragon resistance spell on any mob, but I really have no clue.<br>
<br>
Lastly, there's the choice of unresistable.  However, if they make the spell unresistable, it'll be so little damage so as to not throw off normal exp mobs, that it might as well not be on there for boss mobs.  This is why I'd rather have weapons that proc something like Avatar and Savagery, instead of damage, or stuns or snares. <p>~~
